(43, 10, 'Management of Conflict', NULL, '<p>Conflicts are often a result of misunderstanding or miscommunication. Since misunderstanding or miscommunication is common, conflicts are meant to also be common. It also arises from differences in perspectives, goals, and values. However, the way conflicts are managed plays a crucial role in determining their outcomes.</p>\n<p>Throughout my life, I have experienced conflicts with my family, friends, and peers, and my approach to addressing them has evolved as I matured. During my childhood, I noticed that</p>\n<p>when faced with conflicts, I tended to avoid them. As a little kid, it seemed like I lacked the ability to confront and resolve conflicts effectively. In elementary school, I of', 0, '2023-12-08 14:08:01', NULL, '2023-12-08 07:08:01', '<p>Conflicts are often a result of misunderstanding or miscommunication. Since misunderstanding or miscommunication is common, conflicts are meant to also be common. It also arises from differences in perspectives, goals, and values. However, the way conflicts are managed plays a crucial role in determining their outcomes.</p><p>Throughout my life, I have experienced conflicts with my family, friends, and peers, and my approach to addressing them has evolved as I matured. During my childhood, I noticed that</p><p>when faced with conflicts, I tended to avoid them. As a little kid, it seemed like I lacked the ability to confront and resolve conflicts effectively. In elementary school, I often felt inferior to my classmates. When conflicts arose, such as having a different approach to a group activity, I usually deferred to their decision, thinking that they knew better than I did. Unfortunately, this</p><p>occasionally led to feelings of disappointment, as I recognized that my ideas could have been valuable in those situations.</p><p>When I reached high school, my approach to resolving conflicts shifted towards confrontation. For instance, when my older brother tells me that I do not have the right to</p><p>criticize the government, I tend to confront him. I present various reasons, citing the democratic nature of our country, the role of politicians as public servants, and many other points in support</p><p>of my perspective. However, I&#39;ve noticed that this confrontation sometimes only intensifies the disagreement. Now that I am in college, I have learned to change the subject whenever we discuss</p><p>issues that might cause conflicts between my friends and me. For instance, in my faith, I believe that homosexuality is a sin, but I do not condemn homosexual people outside of my faith.</p><p>Nevertheless, I feel that discussing our perspectives on this topic could lead to disagreement. Therefore, I choose to resolve conflicts through diffusion.</p><p>Reflecting on my conflict management approach, I&#39;ve observed a tendency to diffuse situations, steering away from potential conflicts. As much as possible, my goal is to foster</p><p>harmony in my relationships with those around me. I firmly believe that this approach not only promotes love and peace but also underscores the importance of humility&mdash;occasionally, we</p><p>must set aside our pride.</p>', 'public'),
