mp&rsquo;s &ldquo;Bo&icirc;te-en-Valise,&rdquo; a suitcase containing images of his &ldquo;readymade,&rdquo; encapsulated the unpleasant impacts of relocation, a state of transition and a sense of having left one&#39;s native culture (Moore, 2011). Duchamp&rsquo;s &ldquo;readymade&rdquo; only grew popularity 50 years after, what&rsquo;s beautiful about this is that he intentionally twisted and willfully misinterpreted the meaning of his art and his memories. This approach reveal his personality, rather than historical accuracy (Moore, 2011). Old memory became something new after years that memory was created in the physical world for the sake of adopting to the current person&rsquo;s identity and the present and everchanging times. This everchanging phenomena is very similar to what was indicated in the article of Flores (2017a) about the conflict between art history and globalization. In the said article, Flores said that the documentation of art history got tricker because of the decolonialization that happened throughout the world. The mainstream and western way of analyzing and documentation of different types of art is of no use anymore and should be reconceptualize and recalibrated Flores (2017a).&nbsp;</p>', 'public'),
(47, 7, 'Speech Ni Zion Ramillo III', NULL, 'What if I told you I can make you into a Mathematician, at the very least try to, during my time here on stage. I will not show you complicated formulas, how to solve for x, or crunch big numbers. No. The sort of math that I want you to be familiar with is the practice of common sense. But in particular, why do I say that the most we need to be familiar with is common sense? Because both Mathematics and Common sense are governed by logic and intuition. If we know it to be true then it is not impossible to say that it might be true in another situation. This is what I think is the essence of Mathematics.A significant number of people have claimed that yes Mathematics is useful but only on the', 0, '2023-12-08 18:05:11', NULL, '2023-12-08 11:05:11', '<p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\' id=\"isPasted\">What if I told you I can make you into a Mathematician, at the very least try to, during my time here on stage. I will not show you complicated formulas, how to solve for x, or crunch big numbers. No. The sort of math that I want you to be familiar with is the practice of common sense. But in particular, why do I say that the most we need to be familiar with is common sense? Because both Mathematics and Common sense are governed by logic and intuition. If we know it to be true then it is not impossible to say that it might be true in another situation. This is what I think is the essence of Mathematics.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:26.25pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>A significant number of people have claimed that yes Mathematics is useful but only on the premise of basic arithmetic and the fields of engineering. But I would like to argue that all these applications are just a side effect of Mathematics and our ability to exercise our common sense. Initially, during our time in high school, we were taught what to think about problems, saying &ldquo;It has to be this way and only this way&ldquo;. We were introduced to it as if It was undeniable, restricting, not creative. It was taught in a way that feels like all the answers were handed to you without knowing what the answers mean. If only we were taught in a way that shows us how we should think whenever we have a problem. That is all that mathematics is, it asks of us &ldquo;How well do you think?&rdquo;.</p><h1 style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:41.5pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:110%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Logic</h1><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Logic, (Cheng, 2019) defines logic as a means of clarity, a consistent clarity that everyone no matter the perspective arrives at some form or degree of the same conclusions. For it has been debated upon for thousands of years beforehand, creating solid grounds of foundations to claim that it is true. Logic as Cheng describes is a form of consensus and brings in the power of the majority into play. Where everyone agrees on a certain ground.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>According to Cheng that there has always been a gap between the preconceived notions of mathematics and it has been devalued and some of its powers ignored, however, if we are able to push through mathematics, till we get to a higher degree of mathematics, as Cheng put it, It is simply the study of logical reasoning and how we put it well into practice.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:0cm;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>However, there are some drawbacks when we think about how mathematics is derived logically according to (Mitchelmore &amp; White, 2012), the notion of logic is abstract, such that it disconnects us from the concrete world and turns into a more theoretical way of thought, which are drawn from certain assumptions and experiences which can be dangerous whenever faced within pressuring moments. A blockquote argument derived from Godel&rsquo;s incompleteness theorem:</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:27.1pt;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:32.0pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>&ldquo;Historically, mathematics has seen increasing use of axiomatics, especially over the last two centuries. For example, numbers were initially mathematical objects based on the empirical idea of quantity. Then mathematicians such as Dedekind and Peano reconceptualized numbers in axiom systems which were independent of the idea of quantity. &ldquo;</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:27.05pt;margin-bottom:26.25pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>They are stating that mathematics is only defined within axioms or a set of rules to make each idea concise and consistent and has to stand the test of time. It should not go beyond what the &ldquo;rules of the game&rdquo; want, but it is difficult to say that it is always the case for there are contradictions that linger within the field of Mathematics and if these contradictions break the boundaries of logic then it breaks Mathematics itself.</p><h1 style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:13.75pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:110%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Intuition</h1><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:27.0pt;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Intuition, is the mystical feeling, a vision, or a stream of overflowing ideas. How do we go about defining this prospect? According to (Burton,1999) intuition is not something concrete or something grounded in reality but is something directly affected by your ability to visualize a situation within your mind. In his interviews with different mathematicians, for example, Ian Stewart in 1995, Ian stated intuition is an intrinsic part of human nature, a sort of instinct, and that this instinctive mechanism varies in terms of its host. Being able to visualize the situations at hand helps us holistically discern the possibilities of solving the situation at hand.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:27.05pt;margin-bottom:26.25pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Burton has also stated that there are many complications of how this intuition is an individualistic power, a power that cannot be taught by other people and it must come from within the person wanting enough to gain it. Burton&rsquo;s interviewees within his study stated that intuition is a form of accumulated knowledge and that we can&rsquo;t have intuition without getting ourselves into the action, without the practice the duller our intuition becomes and the more we practice training our minds the more our intuition grows. It is simply saying that intuition and experience go hand in hand and sometimes gaining experience is harder when we are faced with unfortunate circumstances, for example, bad teachers or lack of access to education. Where experience is based on your circumstances.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:41.5pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:left;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:110%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'><strong>References:</strong></p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:.1pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Burton, L. (1999). Why Is Intuition so Important to Mathematicians but Missing from Mathematics&nbsp; &nbsp;Education?&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>For&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;the&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Learning&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;of&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Mathematics</em>,&nbsp;<em>19</em>(3),&nbsp;&nbsp;27&ndash;32.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:29.35pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>http://www.jstor.org/stable/40248307</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:29.7pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Cheng, E. (2019). The Art of Logic: How to Make Sense in a World that Doesn&#39;t. Basic Books.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:14.35pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:left;text-indent:0cm;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Mitchelmore,&nbsp; &nbsp;M.&nbsp; &nbsp;C.,&nbsp; &nbsp;&amp;amp;&nbsp; &nbsp;White,&nbsp; &nbsp;P.&nbsp; &nbsp;(2012).&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Abstraction&nbsp; &nbsp;in&nbsp; &nbsp;mathematics&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;learning.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.9pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:left;text-indent:0cm;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>Encyclopedia&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;of&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;the&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Sciences&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;of&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Learning,&nbsp;31&ndash;33.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:27.6pt;margin-left:-.25pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:-.5pt;line-height:210%;font-size:16px;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:black;\'>https://doi.org/10.1007/978-1-4419-1428-6_516</p>', 'public'),
(48, 7, 'Intellect Pulitiko', NULL, 'Economics follows figures, but this does not necessarily define the reality of its beneficiaries. Within the Philippines, there exists a large unequal distribution of wealth, as well as a lack of generated jobs. However, statistics and figures indicate the contrary, showing an increase in wealth being generated in our country. Sonny Asia introduces to us that the reality is that there is no contradiction between the data and the experience, for by design, it was not made for the people; it was made so that our elite benefits. Our Philippine economy is based on a capitalist architecture where competition is encouraged and is self-regulating. However, this architecture suffocates the uncompeti', 0, '2023-12-08 18:06:36', NULL, '2023-12-08 11:06:36', '<p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:-.55pt;margin-bottom:14.4pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:35.5pt;line-height:125%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;color:black;\' id=\"isPasted\">Economics follows figures, but this does not necessarily define the reality of its beneficiaries. Within the Philippines, there exists a large unequal distribution of wealth, as well as a lack of generated jobs. However, statistics and figures indicate the contrary, showing an increase in wealth being generated in our country. Sonny Asia introduces to us that the reality is that there is no contradiction between the data and the experience, for by design, it was not made for the people; it was made so that our elite benefits. Our Philippine economy is based on a capitalist architecture where competition is encouraged and is self-regulating. However, this architecture suffocates the uncompetitive, who are often the poorest people in the Philippines. In the words of Sonny Asia, &ldquo;Economic growth means nothing if the people are not feeling it.&rdquo;</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:-.55pt;margin-bottom:14.4pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:35.5pt;line-height:125%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;color:black;\'>Now, the underlying question is the role of government institutions in our economic problems. The main role of our government institutions is to regulate, manage, and create policies that benefit the many. However, our government is not taking responsibility to benefit the many, where policies are made by only a select few and are based on elite-centric ideals. These policies are being justified by our government, claiming they will benefit the many through social welfare and infrastructure. However, Sonny Asia states that this is completely untrue. The majority of these benefits are concentrated in the richest urban economy, and social welfare is highly commoditized, such as in our health sectors. Our poorest people, our farmers, are being squeezed on different fronts and are being sacrificed, creating long-term problems like compromising our food security, all in the name of short-term solutions and prioritizing what the market says, not what economic development demands. Government propaganda perpetuates these underlying issues through false statistics and figures that falsely narrate that these policies are working and benefiting the interests of the many.</p><p style=\'margin-top:0cm;margin-right:-.55pt;margin-bottom:14.4pt;margin-left:-.75pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:35.5pt;line-height:125%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;color:black;\'>Now, it is easy to demonize our government; however, Sonny Asia states that the government as a whole is not the problem. Instead, it is the few people who dictate our policies that are the issues we need to address. We can address this by gaining more allies, organizing our movements, and mobilizing our people to demand and fight against inequality and corruption. We can no longer rely on our government to solve these issues; we have the responsibility to contribute to addressing these problems because we too are part of this system. Knowledge is cumulative, and if we continue to learn from our mistakes and triumphs, we can gradually create a system that benefits all Filipinos equally.</p>', 'public');
